'''Nouhad Wadie Haddad'''{{efn|{{langx|engvar=gb|ar|نهاد وديع حداد|Nuhād Wadīʿ Ḥaddād}}, {{IPA|apc-LB|nʊˈhaːd waˈdiːʕ ħadˈdaːd|link=yes}}.}} (born 20 November 1934 or 21 November 1935),{{efn|name=birth}} known professionally as '''Fairuz''',{{efn|Also spelled '''Fairouz''', '''Feyrouz''' or '''Fayrouz'''; {{langx|engvar=gb|ar|فيروز|Fayrūz|links=no}}, {{IPA|ar|fajˈruːz|pron}}.}} is a Lebanese singer. She is widely considered an iconic vocalist and one of the most celebrated singers in the [[Arab world]], as well as a symbol of modern Lebanon. She is popularly known as "The Bird of the East",{{efn|{{langx|engvar=gb|ar|عصفورة الشرق|ʿAṣfūrat aš-Šarq|links=no}}.}} "The [[Cedrus libani|Cedar of Lebanon]]",{{efn|{{langx|engvar=gb|ar|أرزة لبنان|ʾArzat Lubnān|links=no}}.}} "The Moon's Neighbor",{{efn|{{langx|engvar=gb|ar|جارة القمر|Jārat al-Qamar|links=no}}.}} "The Voice of Lebanon",{{efn|{{langx|engvar=gb|ar|صوت لبنان|Ṣawt Lubnān|links=no}}.}} and "Our Ambassador to the Stars",{{efn|{{langx|engvar=gb|ar|سفيرتنا إلى النجوم|Safīratnā ilā n-Nujūm|links=no}}.}} among others.{{efn|Attributed to multiple references:<ref>{{cite news |author=Nora Boustany |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/opinions/1987/04/26/the-sad-voice-of-beirut/29f5d2ab-715a-4ece-9fc8-038a824a1a68/ |title=The Sad Voice of Beirut |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=26 April 1987 }}</ref><ref name="lend">{{Cite web|first1=Ian|last1=Black|url=http://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/jul/29/fairouz-diva-middle-east|title=Fans lend their voices to Fairouz, the silenced diva|date=July 29, 2010|website=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref><ref name=Lebanese>{{cite web |title= Lebanese diva Fairuz's concert delights Syrian fans |url= http://afp.google.com/article/ALeqM5gcai-V_hhTYTsU6-3wNqP2w-H_JQ |publisher= Agence France-Presse |date= 28 January 2009 |access-date= 2009-09-28 |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20090707192334/http://afp.google.com/article/ALeqM5gcai-V_hhTYTsU6-3wNqP2w-H_JQ |archive-date= 7 July 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author= Khaled Yacoub |title= Lebanese diva arouses emotion, controversy in Syria |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/entertainmentNews/idUSL2874028520080128?feedType=RSS&feedName=entertainmentNews |work= Reuters |date= 28 January 2008 |access-date=2009-09-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.skynewsarabia.com/varieties/792871-%D9%81%D9%8A%D8%B1%D9%88%D8%B2--80-%D8%B9%D8%A7%D9%85%D8%A7-%D8%B7%D8%B1%D8%A8-%D9%82%D9%8A%D8%AB%D8%A7%D8%B1%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B3%D9%85%D8%A7%D8%A1|title=فيروز .. 80 عاما من طرب 'قيثارة السماء' |trans-title=Fayrouz.. 80 years of singing "Heaven's Harp" |work=[[Sky News Arabia]] |language=ar |date=2015-11-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-12-07 |title=Virtually Unknown in the West, But She's an Icon of the Arab World |url=https://www.messynessychic.com/2023/12/07/virtually-unknown-in-the-west-but-shes-an-icon-of-the-arab-world/ |access-date=2024-02-20 |website=Messy Nessy Chic}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-11-21 |title=فيروز في يوم ميلادها الـ87.. سفيرتنا إلى النجوم |language=ar |url=https://www.addustour.com/articles/1315086-%D9%81%D9%8A%D8%B1%D9%88%D8%B2-%D9%81%D9%8A-%D9%8A%D9%88%D9%85-%D9%85%D9%8A%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%AF%D9%87%D8%A7-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%8087-%D8%B3%D9%81%D9%8A%D8%B1%D8%AA%D9%86%D8%A7-%D8%A5%D9%84%D9%89-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%86%D8%AC%D9%88%D9%85 |access-date=2025-12-11 |website=[[Ad-Dustour (Jordan)|Ad-Dustour]]}}</ref>}}

Fairuz began her musical career as a teenager at the national radio station in Lebanon in the late 1940s as a [[choir|chorus member]]. Her first major hit, "Itab", was released in 1952 and made her an instant star in the Arab world. In the summer of 1957, Fairuz held her first live performance at the [[Baalbeck International Festival]] where she was awarded with the honour of "Cavalier", the highest medal for artistic achievement by Lebanese president [[Camille Chamoun]]. Fairuz's fame spread throughout the Arab world in the 1950s and 1960s, leading her to  perform outside of Lebanon in various Arab capitals, including [[Damascus]], [[Amman]], [[Cairo]], [[Rabat]], [[Algiers]], and [[Tunis]].

Fairuz has received honours and distinctions in multiple countries, including Lebanon, Syria, Jordan, Palestine, Tunisia, the United States, Egypt, and France. Throughout her career, she headlined at the most important venues in the world, such as [[Albert Hall]] and [[Royal Festival Hall]] in London, [[Carnegie Hall]], [[Lincoln Center]] and [[United Nations General Assembly]] Lobby in New York, [[Olympia (Paris)|the Olympia]] and [[Salle Pleyel]] in Paris, and the [[Odeon of Herodes Atticus]] in Athens.

In a career spanning over six decades, Fairuz has recorded nearly 1500 songs, released more than 80 [[albums]], performed in 20 [[Musical theatre|musicals]], and sold over 150 million records worldwide, making her one of the highest selling Middle-Eastern artists of all time, and one of the best-selling music artists in the world.{{efn|Attributed to multiple references:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenationalnews.com/arts-culture/eight-reasons-why-fairouz-is-the-greatest-arab-diva-of-all-time-1.186719|title=Eight reasons why Fairouz is the greatest Arab diva of all time|date=21 November 2016|website=The National}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.aljadid.com/music/fairouza_voice_star_mystery.html |title= Fairouz: a Voice, a Star, a Mystery |author= Sami Asmar |date= Spring 1995 |work= Al Jadid |access-date= 14 January 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100123074747/http://www.aljadid.com/music/fairouza_voice_star_mystery.html |archive-date= 23 January 2010 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.albawaba.com/entertainment/iconic-fairouz-remains-most-listened-arab-singer-she-turns-80-771638|title=Iconic Fairouz remains most listened-to Arab singer as she turns 80|website=Al Bawaba}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title= Fairouz&nbsp;– Legend and Legacy |last= Boulos |first= Sargon |year= 1981 |publisher= Forum for International Art and Culture |url= http://almashriq.hiof.no/lebanon/700/780/fairuz/legend/biography.html |access-date= 13 January 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.forbesmiddleeast.com/en/list/arab-stars-on-the-global-stage/item/1/ |title=Arab Stars on the Global Stage |access-date=14 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181015003049/https://www.forbesmiddleeast.com/en/list/arab-stars-on-the-global-stage/item/1/ |archive-date=15 October 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>}}
